MK-001 | mini-kernel / photo-sharing
Implement photo-sharing mini-kernel: src/index.ts extending MiniKernelBase. Tables: photo_sharing_items (id, author_id, storage_url, caption, tags[], likes, created_at). GraphQL mutations: uploadPhoto(storageUrl, caption, tags), deletePhoto(id), likePhoto(id). processFeed() queries by author_id IN followees ORDER BY created_at DESC. processEvent() handles user.deleted cascade.
TEST1: POST /feed with valid userIds returns array of photo objects with id, storage_url, caption, likes
TEST2: POST /events with {type:'user.deleted', actorId:'<uuid>'} removes all author's rows from photo_sharing_items
TEST3: GraphQL mutation uploadPhoto returns created photo with id and createdAt
TEST4: GET /health returns {status:'ok', kernelId:'photo-sharing'}
TEST5: GET /capabilities returns eventSubscriptions including 'user.follow' and 'content.like'
TEST6: Mini-kernel registers with Discovery service within 5s of startup (check GET localhost:4002/kernels)

MK-002 | mini-kernel / messaging
Implement messaging mini-kernel. Tables: messages (id, group_id, author_id, ciphertext BYTEA, created_at), message_groups (id, name, member_ids UUID[]). All message content stored as AES-256-GCM ciphertext — kernel never sees plaintext. GraphQL: sendMessage(groupId, ciphertext), createGroup(name, memberIds), getMessages(groupId, limit, cursor). processFeed() returns empty array (messaging has no public feed). WebSocket /ws/:groupId endpoint for real-time push via NATS subscription.
TEST1: GraphQL sendMessage returns message id and createdAt; ciphertext stored verbatim in DB (no decryption attempted)
TEST2: GET /health returns ok
TEST3: WebSocket connection to /ws/<groupId> receives new messages within 200ms of sendMessage call
TEST4: processFeed() always returns {items:[]} regardless of userIds input
TEST5: createGroup with 3 memberIds stores all 3 in message_groups.member_ids array
TEST6: NATS publishes event 'messaging.message.sent' on every sendMessage with {groupId, authorId}

